</noscript></center><div class='main'><div class='mainheader'><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="2b892ec0285573b72fb47141def34480" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></div><div class='maincontent'><BR><font class="h1font"> Ranger Review<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/wars/main/mpage.php?member=20244'>Ben "tragicmishap" Kissling</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/wars/main/mpage.php?member=20244&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 8, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Go here for the preview of the new Ranger unit from the Reserves set to be released November 10:<br />
http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=ah/aam/ah20060906c<br />
<br />
When I saw this unit, I nearly pissed myself because it changes the game forever. The Ranger does two things. First, the Allies will now be able to play a defense 5 infantry swarm and still have points to spare for support. Secondly, the SS-Panzergrenadier’s supremacy is challenged once again, and this time it’s serious. Let’s go through this groundbreaking new unit bit by bit in terms of the 100 point standard map game.<br />
<br />
Basic stats:<br />
Even without the SAs this piece would be a great one. A cheap defense 5 infantry unit is exactly what the Allies needed. 9/7 AI and a Close Assault of 7 is pretty standard for elite infantry units, though not as good as the SS-PG.<br />
<br />
Lead the Way:<br />
This is what makes the Ranger nearly the SS-PG’s equal. Basically, it adds one die once per turn to any attack value the Ranger has. In addition, you can use that extra die if you want to reroll a movement roll. In the unlikely event that you will be faced with a choice here, it’s a no brainer. So make it easy on yourself and in your mind just add one dice to every attack value for the Ranger and call it good. This gives it a 10/8 AI attack and a Close Assault of 8. Just remember that this can only be used once per turn, so if you need to make a defensive fire the choice will be a little harder, but I still think most of the time you will want to use it for your regular attack. The Close Assault is actually higher than the SS-PG. As an SA, Lead the Way is less than interesting. It makes the Ranger competitive with the SS-PG straight up (which they could’ve done just by increasing the attack rolls), slightly more mobile and slightly better against armor. However, the SS-PG’s Ruthless SA is unequaled by the Ranger, and makes up the difference and then some. Ruthless can be used against infantry or armor and a +1 modifier against any disrupted unit is definitely better than an extra Close Assault die or *ho-hum* getting another crack at crossing a stream or Barbed Wire. Even scarier, I don’t think that the Ruthless SA has seen it’s full potential until now. Up until the Ranger, the competitive Allied defense 5 infantry were either Heroes or SE paras. These units will never be disrupted during the attack phase, so Ruthless never applies to them. Defense 4 infantry are inferior to the SS-PG in so many ways that Ruthless was just overkill against them. But now in the Ranger you have a defense 5 infantry that can be disrupted. An undisrupted SS-PG now has a one-shot, one-kill on any disrupted Ranger barring cover rolls. The same cannot be said for the Ranger, to say nothing of the fact that the SS-PGs are less likely to be disrupted because of the ubiquitous SS-Haupsturmfuhrer and the fact that if both units are disrupted the SS-PG has a huge advantage. The Red Devil Captain can help here, as it subtracts 1 from those SS-PG cover rolls, so hopefully there will be less SS-PGs than Rangers come round two of firing when Ruthless will begin to take its toll.<br />
<br />
Spotter subtype:<br />
At first this seems like a really great deal. I’ve heard people on the boards blurt out, “An elite infantry unit that also acts as a spotter? Power Creep!” Not so fast. Every spotter unit has the Spotter subtype as well as the Spotter SA. The Spotter subtype allows Indirect Fire to go through this unit. The Spotter SA increases the attack dice of planes. The Ranger has the Spotter subtype, but not the Spotter SA. Basically, the Ranger can now spot for the Russian mortar and the Priest. Yes, in the entire game those are the only two things the Spotter subtype will do for this unit. The Priest is nice but it’s too expensive when you can get two mortars plus change for the same price. Bombardment is not worth having an extra shot, and in general it’s a bad idea to sink so many points into such an expensive unit. The only mortar worth having, the M1 81mm, only needed a US unit as a Spotter anyway. If you’re not a nation nitpicker, than you can field the Russian heavy mortar instead of the US one for one less point and not have to spend 8 points on a Spotter as you would have before. If you just want your basic infantry to spot for the heavies, you can save one point and use the Russian heavy. Big deal. You sacrifice the real power of the US mortar, that is to hit units that can avoid everything else by using a highly mobile spotter, to save one or two points in a build. Basically what we have here is WotC wanting to find a subtype for the Ranger that made it interesting and unique but didn’t make it more powerful, which is exactly what it does.<br />
<br />
Conclusion:<br />
An Allied infantry build is now competitive. Before this, the Allies’ only defense 5 infantry were Heroes, Screaming Eagles and Defiant Paratroopers. Of course, there was a cheap defense 5 substitute in the Veteran SMLE, but all in all the Allies did not have strong enough infantry units to really compete in the infantry sphere. The reason is because of the 15 unit limit. Because of the limit, the number of 3 and 4 point infantry you can field is too small to overcome the more expensive defense 5 infantry. As a result, the Allies either had to go all armor (which happened quite often) or pull out some tricks such as the KV-1/Cossack Cpt or highly mobile spotters for the M1 81mm mortar to take down the inevitable SS-PG horde. With players of equal skill, these limited options made it difficult, though not impossible, for the Allied player and left much to be desired. With an all armor build, you still have the all important problem of holding the objective against the Axis infantry. A KV-1 Cossack/Combo is very good for that, but that’s a lot of points to sink into a unit that is likely to survive, but unlikely to kill anything. A Croc sacrifices some survivability and gains a better chance of killing SS-PGs as well as armor. These two units together are actually pretty dang good, except for the fact that you’ve got 75% of your points wrapped up into basically two units. The mortar was nice, but fielding too many of them and a dedicated spotting unit without enough infantry support left the Allied player castrated when turn 7 comes around, as he/she has a lot of points sunk into units that can’t even think about taking the objective. As for the defense 5 Allied infantry, the Screaming Eagles are clearly the best, since you can only field one Hero and for one more point than the Defiant Paras you get Hard Charger. Now, Screaming Eagle Paratroopers are good, but you pay 2 points for the Paratrooper ability which is too much. Mobility is nice, but in general firepower and defense eventually win out on the standard maps, since you can be on the objective in two turns or less even with ordinary infantry. To field an SE Para swarm that can compete on equal terms with an SS-PG/SS-Haupsturmfuhrer force you will have no points left, while the Axis player has lots of extra points to field more goodies. Now with the Ranger costing only 5 points, the Allies can field a comparable Ranger/Red Devil Cpt OR Eagle-eyed NCO combo for the same price and use the extra points to play around and figure something out to deal with heavy armor. The SS infantry are still superior, but at least the Allies can now compete enough in the infantry battle to allow the Shermans, Crocs and mortars to make up the difference.<br />
<br />
Effect on the Metagame:<br />
Gameplay will become more competitive, equal and exciting. We will see more defense 5 infantry swarms now that the Allies also have a great basic defense 5 infantry unit. We will see more creative and effective armor builds as players try to figure out ways to one-up all the elite infantry swarms that will be played now. We will see better Allied combined arms teams since the Rangers are cheap and easy to fill in those extra points with. In short, we will begin to see the actual character of both the US and German nations, and to a larger extent the Axis and Allied factions, play out in the metagame and on equal terms. This piece is in every sense of the word exactly what this game needed. Now excuse me while I go change my shorts. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/wars/articles/articles.php?id=6410&view=1&PHPSESSID=2b892ec0285573b72fb47141def34480'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/wars/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=2b892ec0285573b72fb47141def34480'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/wars/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=2b892ec0285573b72fb47141def34480'> become a registered member</a></font></div></div>


